Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of the Ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was adopted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as a second country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ECA in 1994 and actively participated in a number of Agency projects over the years.
But the way to the cosmos of Poland began much earlier.
By the time World War II, Polish enthusiasts had traveled into space, but this was not always understood.
I recall, for example, the lecture of A. Sternfeld, which on 6 December 1933 presented to Warsaw's astronomical observatory the idea of his innovative work "Introduction into cosmonautique".
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience with an open mind, and a few years later Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won Robert Esno-Peltri's award and Andre Luis Hirsch for "Introduction into spacecraft".
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), mentioned earlier, later became a major advocate of astronomy and cosmonautism.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a famous world propagandist of cosmonautism, and his contribution was assessed, including that one of the craters on the other side of the moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925, a missile - equipped railway vehicle was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as was the project ' s details.
It is not even clear that a missile should have been used to drive or to brake the vehicle.
The information about this site is only known from the press of that era.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery has been thinking about rockets.
The study was conducted by the Arms Technology Section, in cooperation with Professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzyck.
The remaining materials show that the studies have come to a stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of the German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the specialized press came up with the idea of a photo-electric missile by Rogozinski, and the following year, the work "Air Torpedo and Air Bomb" by the author of Leviva-Kzioblockko was released.
Both projects were designed for the military use of rocket engines.
The Temporary Scientific and Advisory Committee (the Temporary Committee of the Doradczo-Naukowa) was involved in all projects for the military use of missile technology before the war.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of work, work was completed as a result of the beginning of the war.
The next scientific work on space was published in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautic Society (Polish Astronautic Society).
For the first time, it was mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problem, where four articles on astronomy were published.
In one of them, Professor M. Sobotovic suggested that a society be organized to deal with space science.
At the time, the projects of artificial satellites were already underway, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, Polish Astronautic Society (POA) has tried to enter the International Astronautic Federation (based in 1951) and has become its true member in the fall of the POA.
And next year, the first President of POA Kazimez Zarankevich (1902 - 1959) became Vice-President of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in that position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, POA has made a significant contribution to the development of a very successful meteorological rocket RM (Raketa Meteorologicnza), which has become the first Polish research rocket.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first was launched on 10 October 1958.
The rocket capable of overcoming 1800 m was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
An improved version of RM-1A was subsequently built and two-stage RM-2 rocket tests were conducted in the Black Desert in 1959.
The rocket was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already capable of doing this scientific work - the RM-34 rocket could exceed 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high wind.
However, further development was suspended in 1962.
The first RM-type successor was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket with a total length of 510 cm and a primary weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (described as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which were different from the size of the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had an area of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B - 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C - 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight distance for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first summer tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a starting weight of 380 kg was able to extract a useful load of 10 kg at a height of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland ' s accession to COSPAR in 1960 and the establishment of the National Committee of COSPAR two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos programme, Poland participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslav Hermasevski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
