Sabo: "The Germans must play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stefan Sabo, an expert on relations between the United States and Europe, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first realized that it was voting against the Palestinian application for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
Why?
Stefan Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany must now be cautious about its special relations with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it also does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence, while not speaking too critical of Israel.
During the rise in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the introduction of a restricted area for flights.
NATO has finally put forward this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
The issue is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, that is, from a policy that has been managed by the United States to a German foreign policy.
The situation is further complicated by the lack of a coherent common policy for Europeans.
Thus, the Germans are again placed between the two fronts.
They were expected to play a more independent role, but they did not get used to it.
I believe that as long as they're just playing their part, they're on their way to "more normal" foreign policy.
Such an external policy carried out by France or the United Kingdom.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It is a willingness to take a position for its own national interests, not dependent on the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policies, i.e. on exports and links with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany ' s economic interests differ considerably from those of other major States, and Germany should therefore protect its interests.
Did these economic interests affect the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Persian Gulf States.
It therefore needs to be careful not to offend the public and elites in Arab countries.
In any case, it plays its part.
But I wouldn't give this too much importance, it's not a completely unilateral relationship.
But in any case, this plays an important role in German calculations.
Did Germany harm its relations with the United States by refraining from making important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States, an understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as it was in the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will gain some respect in this way.
This indicates that it should be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests should be taken into account.
There are various views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
On the contrary, the United States had made a clear statement about the veto.
Is there a difference between the United States and many European States?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama Government has a deep understanding of the European position.
But in the context of the local political situation, of course, the Government cannot take such a position openly.
I believe that significant differences in opinion are not as important as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, note that Obama is not in any way out of line with Netanyahu's policy.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the situation of an important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, the Germans would be a little bit easier if there were a united, unopposed European policy, but now it is not.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and are forced to act instead, based only on their own vision of the situation.
That's how they deal with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will play a leading role in developing a common European position.
It is understandable that it is not easy for Germany, even if it is linked to Israel.
This subject has always been sensitive.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, won't it really take on the leading role?
Or is the leading role still difficult for Germany?
Germany has not yet become accustomed to this, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany plays an important role, the most diverse anti-German feelings are expressed.
The Germans don't just deal with it.
Of course, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this respect, Germany is in a much more difficult situation than the United States.
It should take into account the different neighbours and opinions, and this was not easy.
Thus, the U.S. influence in European policy is constantly weakening, but at this point the EU is not filling this vacuum, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
Even if you do not like it, it is an unpleasant thing to do, or it is an abomination to you.
Stefan Sabo, Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, where academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly investigate the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Sabo is a member of the German Marshall Fund, which specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
